title: H.S. girls volleyball notebook: Oct. 13, 2015
text:
H.S. girls volleyball notebook: Oct. 13, 2015 October 13, 2015 Last updated: Tuesday, October 13, 2015, 1:21 AM The Record Print 
BERGEN TOURNAMENT: Unbeaten NV/Old Tappan, No. 1 in The Record girls volleyball Top 20, is expected to earn the top spot, and reigning champ Immaculate Heart the No. 2 at tonight’s seeding meeting for the Bergen County tournament. Unbeaten River Dell could earn No. 3, Paramus No. 4 and NV/Demarest No. 5. The Record will post the list of entries today and pairings tonight on its Varsity Aces Web page: northjersey.com/varsityaces. 
BEARS CLIMBING: Hawthorne (7-5) has won six consecutive matches, with senior L Barbara Colizza leading the way. In three wins last week, Colizza totaled 58 digs to raise her season total to a team-leading 151, and she served a dozen or more points in two of the wins. Junior H Hannah Frascella leads the Bears in kills with 124, and senior S Marianna Stas is tops in assists with 128. 
RISING TIGERS: No. 8 Tenafly (13-3) has won nine of its past 10 matches entering today’s battle versus No. 12 Pascack Valley (6-5), and two seniors, M Elle O’Brien and S Anna Stein, have raised their play. Over the past two weeks, O’Brien has 67 kills and 10 blocks, coach Jeff Koehler said, while Stein has smoothly quarterbacked an attack led by second-team All-North Jersey senior H Noy Chorin. 
PALADINS’ PROGRESS: Paramus Catholic (7-9) today hosts rival and No. 18 Holy Angels (9-3) fresh off Monday’s three-set home victory over Fort Lee. H Danielle Sondey has scored key points in tight games, coach Jaime Marzocchi said, and senior L Karah Degnan, a four-year veteran, was exceptional against Fort Lee. "Her defense has really kept us in a lot of games," Marzocchi said. 
GARDEN STATE CHALLENGE: Hunterdon Central became the third New Jersey team to win the title at the eighth annual Garden State Challenge, with host Immaculate Heart, the 2013 winner and four-time reigning Tournament of Champions titlist, reaching Sunday’s quarterfinals at Fairleigh Dickinson in Hackensack. "We just continue to work hard and keep raising our level of play," said IHA coach Maria Nolan. 
QUICKS: Wood-Ridge’s Andrea Marino, in her 11th season coaching her alma mater and 21st overall, earned her 400th victory with Thursday’s 25-22, 26-24 upset over Wallington. … Immaculate Heart owns a two-game lead in the Big North United with two to play and can become the first North Jersey team to clinch its division title with a win today over DePaul. … Standings for the Big North and NJIC can be found on northjersey.com/varsityaces.
